      <p
        style="margin: 4px 0 10px; font-size:12px; font-family:var(--font-mono); letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--text-muted);"
      >
        Component Explorer for Astro
      </p>
      <p class="subtitle">
        Stargaze your components. Zero heavy deps, no throwaway pages. Just <a
          href="https://astro.build"
          target="_blank"
          class="fw-link">Astro</a
        >.
      </p>

      <h2 id="why">Why Stargazer?</h2>
      <p>
        If you've ever built a component-based website (<a
          href="https://astro.build"
          target="_blank"
          class="fw-link">Astro</a
        >, <a href="https://nextjs.org" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
          >Next.js</a
        >, <a href="https://svelte.dev" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
          >Svelte</a
        >, you name it), you've probably done this:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Build a component</li>
        <li>Move on to the next one</li>
        <li>Three weeks later… "wait, what did that Hero look like again?"</li>
        <li>
          Create a random test page, import the component, check it, delete the
          page
        </li>
        <li>Repeat forever</li>
      </ol>
      <p>We all do it. It works, but it's not great.</p>
      <p>
        Stargazer started because I wanted something better. Just list your
        components in <strong>one config file</strong> and get a full visual catalog
        with viewport testing, zoom, and dark mode toggle. It runs inside your existing
        Astro dev server. No extra tools, no extra build step, no heavy install.
      </p>

      <h2 id="inspired">Inspired By</h2>
      <p>This was built on the ideas of some solid tools that already exist:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong
            ><a href="https://storybook.js.org/" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
              >Storybook</a
            ></strong
          > — the OG, massive ecosystem, addon library for days
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong
            ><a href="https://histoire.dev/" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
              >Histoire</a
            ></strong
          > — beautiful, great for <a
            href="https://vuejs.org"
            target="_blank"
            class="fw-link">Vue</a
          > and <a href="https://svelte.dev" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
            >Svelte</a
          >
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong
            ><a href="https://ladle.dev/" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
              >Ladle</a
            ></strong
          > — lightweight Storybook alternative for <a
            href="https://react.dev"
            target="_blank"
            class="fw-link">React</a
          >
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        All great tools. But none of them are built <strong>for Astro</strong>,
        and most come with setup overhead that felt like overkill for what I
        needed.
      </p>

      <h2 id="comparison">Comparison</h2>
      <table>
        <thead
          ><tr
            ><th></th><th>Storybook</th><th>Histoire</th><th>Astro Stargazer</th
            ></tr
          ></thead
        >
        <tbody>
          <tr
            ><td>Install size</td><td>~50MB+</td><td>~15MB</td><td
              ><strong>~0.5MB</strong></td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Config per component</td><td
              >1 <code>.stories</code> file each</td
            ><td>1 <code>.story</code> file each</td><td
              ><strong>1 file total</strong></td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Extra dev server</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td><td
              ><strong>No, uses Astro's</strong></td
            ></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Learning curve</td><td>Decorators, args, controls</td><td
              >Story syntax</td
            ><td><strong>Just a list of paths</strong></td></tr
          >
          <tr
            ><td>Astro-native</td><td>❌</td><td>❌</td><td
              ><strong>✅</strong></td
            ></tr
          >
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          This isn't a Storybook replacement. If you need interactive controls,
          docs generation, or a huge addon ecosystem, Storybook is the right
          choice. Stargazer is for when you just want to <strong
            >see your components</strong
          > quickly.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <strong>Framework components work too.</strong>
          <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" class="fw-link">Astro</a
          > supports <a href="https://react.dev" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
            >React</a
          >, <a href="https://vuejs.org" target="_blank" class="fw-link">Vue</a
          >, <a href="https://svelte.dev" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
            >Svelte</a
          >, <a href="https://www.solidjs.com" target="_blank" class="fw-link"
            >Solid</a
          > and others via islands. If your <code>.astro</code> component imports
          a React button or a Vue card, Stargazer previews it exactly as it would
          render in your real page — hydration and all.
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <h2 id="requirements">Requirements</h2>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Requirement</th><th>Version</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Astro</td><td><strong>≥ 4.9.0</strong> (Astro 5 &amp; 6 ✅)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Node.js</td><td><strong>≥ 18.0.0</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          Framework components (React, Vue, Svelte, Solid…) work out of the box if you already have them set up in your Astro
          project — no extra config needed.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <strong>v1.4.0:</strong> Full compatibility with <strong>Astro 6 / Vite 7</strong>, including <code>@astrojs/cloudflare</code>. Previous versions crashed on startup when the Cloudflare adapter was active.
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <hr />

      <h2 id="install">Install</h2>
      <h3>Option A — <code>astro add</code> (recommended)</h3>
      <pre><code>npx astro add astro-stargazer</code></pre>
      <p>This automatically updates your <code>astro.config.mjs</code>.</p>
      <h3>Option B — Manual</h3>
      <pre><code>npm install astro-stargazer</code></pre>

      <h2 id="config-setup">Config Setup</h2>
      <h3>1. Add to your Astro config</h3>
      <pre><code>// astro.config.mjs
import {'{'} defineConfig {'}'} from 'astro/config';
import stargazer from 'astro-stargazer';

export default defineConfig({'{'} 
  integrations: [stargazer()]
{'}'});</code></pre>

      <h3>2. Create your config (optional)</h3>
      <p>
        No config file needed for basic usage. Stargazer auto-detects layouts from <code>src/layouts/</code>.
        For advanced options (variants, defaults, layout mapping), create <code>stargazer.config.ts</code>:
      </p>
      <pre><code>// stargazer.config.ts (optional)
import {'{'} defineConfig {'}'} from 'astro-stargazer';

export default defineConfig({'{'}
  defaults: {'{'} lang: 'en' {'}'},
{'}'});</code></pre>
      <p>Or run the setup wizard to generate it interactively:</p>
      <pre><code>npx create-stargazer</code></pre>
      <p>Or list components manually with <code>mode: 'files'</code>:</p>
      <pre><code>import {'{'} defineConfig {'}'} from 'astro-stargazer';

export default defineConfig({'{'}
  mode: 'files',
  components: [
    {'{'} name: 'Hero', path: './src/components/Hero.astro', description: 'Landing hero section' {'}'},
    {'{'} name: 'Footer', path: './src/components/Footer.astro' {'}'},
  ],
{'}'});</code></pre>
      <p>That's it. No stories, no decorators, no extra syntax.</p>

      <h2 id="run">Run</h2>
      <pre><code>npm run dev</code></pre>
      <p>
        Open <strong><code>/stargazer</code></strong> in your browser — check your
        terminal for the exact port (usually <code>4321</code>). 🔭
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          Works on macOS, Linux and Windows — pure Node.js, no native binaries.
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <hr />

      <h2 id="config-reference">Configuration Reference</h2>
      <p>
        Create <code>stargazer.config.ts</code> (or <code>.js</code> / <code
          >.mjs</code
        >) in your project root:
      </p>
      <pre><code>import type {'{'} StargazerConfig {'}'} from 'astro-stargazer';

const config: StargazerConfig = {'{'} ... {'}'};
export default config;</code></pre>

      <h3>Options</h3>
      <table>
